<grammar>
<section>
<title> Gerunds (&lt;i&gt;-ing&lt;/i&gt; forms) </title>
<sectiontitle>Gerunds (&lt;i&gt;-ing&lt;/i&gt; forms) are like nouns or pronouns. We use them as the subject or object of a sentence.</sectiontitle>
<titlesound>pi_gram11_1_1.mp3</titlesound>
<text1>The subject:</text1>
<text1a>&lt;b&gt;Spending&lt;/b&gt; time with friends is important.</text1a>
<sound1>pi_gram11_1_2.mp3</sound1>
<text2>The object:</text2>
<text2a>I hate &lt;b&gt;buying &lt;/b&gt;presents.</text2a>
<sound2>pi_gram11_1_3.mp3</sound2>
<sectiontitle2>We also use gerunds (-&lt;i&gt;ing&lt;/i&gt; forms) after prepositions.</sectiontitle2>
<titlesound2>pi_gram11_1_4.mp3</titlesound2>
<text3></text3>
<text3a>She's crazy &lt;b&gt;about shopping. &lt;/b&gt;</text3a>
<sound3>pi_gram11_1_5.mp3</sound3>
<text4></text4>
<text4a>She's keen &lt;b&gt;on travelling. </text4a>
<sound4>pi_gram11_1_6.mp3</sound4>
</section>
<section>
<title> Gerunds (&lt;i&gt;-ing&lt;/i&gt; forms) after verbs of liking and disliking</title>
<sectiontitle>We use gerunds (&lt;i&gt;-ing&lt;/i&gt; forms) after many phrases expressing likes and dislikes.</sectiontitle>
<titlesound>pi_gram11_1_7.mp3</titlesound>
<text1></text1>
<text1a>I &lt;b&gt;really enjoy &lt;/b&gt;cooking.</text1a>
<sound1>pi_gram11_1_8.mp3</sound1>
<text2></text2>
<text2a>He &lt;b&gt;can't stand&lt;/b&gt; being late.</text2a>
<sound2>pi_gram11_1_9.mp3</sound2>
<sectiontitle2></sectiontitle2>
<titlesound2></titlesound2>
<text3></text3>
<text3a></text3a>
<sound3></sound3>
<text4></text4>
<text4a></text4a>
<sound4></sound4>
</section>
</grammar>